er=[[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana]]|language=Italian|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| 48\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Lithuania ([[AGATA (organization)|AGATA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.agata.lt/lt/naujienos/savaites-klausomiausi-2020w14/|title=2020 14-os savait\u0117s klausomiausi (TOP 100)|publisher=[[AGATA (organization)|AGATA]]|language=Lithuanian|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| 21\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|61|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|song=Savage|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| New Zealand ([[Recorded Music NZ]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=4848|title=NZ Top 40 Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| 14\n|-\n{{single chart|Portugal|60|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|song=Savage|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|33|date=20200417|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Slovakdigital|20|year=2020|week=15|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Sweden ([[Sverigetopplistan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigetopplistan.se/chart/41?dspy=2020&dspp=16|title=Veckolista Singlar, vecka 16|publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]]|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| 73\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|35|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|song=Savage|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|17|date=20200417|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKrandb|14|date=20200403|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|14|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 14, 2020|refname=Hot 100}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrandbhiphop|7|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrhythmic|25|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]]<ref name=\"RS 100\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/songs/2020-04-01/|title=Top 100 Songs|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| 6\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Region\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| March 6, 2020\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1501 Certified [[300 Entertainment|300]] ([[Warner Music Group|Warner]])\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/savage/1501734515?i=1501734796|title=Savage by Megan Thee Stallion on Apple Music|via=[[Apple Music]]|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| United States\n| April 7, 2020\n| [[Contemporary hit radio|Top 40 radio]]\n|<ref name=\"AllAccess\" />\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Megan Thee Stallion}}\n\n[[Category:Megan Thee Stallion songs]]\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:TikTok songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by J. White Did It]]\n", "name_user": "Ss112", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharts:updated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Savage_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Charles E. Hart", "text_new": "{{other people||Charles Hart (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Charles Edward Hart\n| image         = Lieutenant_General_Charles_Edward_Hart.png\n| caption       = Circa 1956-1960\n| birth_date    = June 17, 1900\n| death_date    = December 9, 1991 (aged 91)\n| birth_place   = [[Fort Washington, Maryland]]\n| death_place   = [[Fort Belvoir]], [[Virginia]]\n| placeofburial = [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance    = {{US}}\n| branch        = {{Army|United States}}\n| serviceyears  = 1924\u20131960\n| rank          = [[File:US-O9 insignia.svg|20px]] [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]]\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = \n| commands      = [[Artillery, 1st Infantry Division]]<br> [[Artillery, 7th Army]]<br>\n[[US Military Assistance Group, Greece]]<br> [[U.S. V Corps|V Corps]]<br>[[Commandant of the Artillery Center & School]]<br>[[Second United States Army|2nd Army]]<br>[[Army Air Defense Command]]\n| battles       = [[World War II]]\n| battles_label = \n| awards        = [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]]<br>[[Legion of Merit]] x2\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n}}\n\n'''Charles Edward Hart''' (June 17, 1900 \u2013 December 9, 1991) born in [[Fort Washington, Maryland]] was a [[General|Commanding General]] of the [[U.S. V Corps|V Corps]] (1954\u20131956) and Commanding General of the Army Air Defense Command (1957\u20131960). He died at [[Fort Belvoir]], [[Virginia]] at the age of 91.\n\n==Early life==\n'''Charles Edward Hart''' was born in Fort Washington, Maryland, the son of Dr. (Colonel) James William Hart and Grace Duncan Hart.<ref>[https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ West Point Memorial] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408213009/https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ |date=April 8, 2014 }}</ref> Hart was a descendant of Private Joseph Hart, a member of the 4th Virginia Regiment during the Revolutionary War.<ref>District of Columbia Sons of the American Revolution Application, National Number 23755.</ref> By 1910 the family had moved to Washington, D.C. where Hart's father had a general practice and served on the staff of the Veteran's Hospital.<ref>13th Federal Census, 1910, District of Columbia.</ref><ref>[https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ West Point Memorial] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408213009/https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ |date=April 8, 2014 }}</ref> Eventually residing in Fort Hunt, Virginia, Hart would attend military drills with his father. After graduating from Western High School in Washington, D.C., Hart began working at a bank while seeking an appointment as a cadet at [[United States Military Academy]].\n\n==Early career==\nHart entered the [[United States Military Academy]] at West Point on July 1, 1920 during the tenure of [[Douglas MacArthur]] as superintendent.<ref>Official Roster of Officers and Cadets for 1924, U.S.M.A., U.S. Military Academy Printing Office, West Point, NY.</ref> He would graduate 298th out of 405 cadets in 1924.<ref>Official Roster of Officers and Cadets for 1924, U.S.M.A., U.S. Military Academy Printing Office, West Point, NY.</ref> While at the Academy Hart was known to be an avid horseman.<ref>Official Roster of Officers and Cadets for 1924, U.S.M.A., U.S. Military Academy Printing Office, West Point, NY.</ref>\n\nFollowing graduation in 1924, Hart was commissioned a [[second lieutenant]] in the Field Artillery, and assigned to the [[4th Field Artillery Regiment]] located at [[Fort Sam Houston]], [[Texas]].<ref>[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/cehart.htm Lt. General Charles Edward Hart Memorial Page, Arlington National Cemetery.]</ref> Shortly after his arrival in Texas he would be transferred to [[Fort McIntosh, Texas]] along the US-Mexican border where he would remain until being transferred to [[Fort Knox]], [[Kentucky]] in 1928. During his tenure in Texas he would serve as adjutant for the [[4th Field Artillery Regiment]] before transferring to the [[3rd Field Artillery Regiment (United States)|3rd Field Artillery Regiment]] also based at Fort McIntosh, Texas. Upon transfer he would continue as an adjutant and serve as Commanding Officer of the Service Battery, 3rd Field Artillery Regiment from 1927 until his transfer in 1928.<ref>[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/cehart.htm Lt. General Charles Edward Hart Memorial Page, Arlington National Cemetery.]</ref>\n\nHart would serve one year at Fort Knox, Kentucky before receiving a promotion to [[1st Lieutenant]] and a transfer to [[Fort Myer]], [[Virginia]] to serve with the [[16th Field Artillery Regiment]]. He would remain there for approximately one year before being sent to the [[United States Field Artillery School]] located in [[Fort Sill]], [[Oklahoma]]. After a year as a student, Hart graduated in 1931 and went to the [[8th Field Artillery Regiment]]. In 1932 Hart would serve the 11th Artillery Brigade (1932-1933) until followed by the [[8th Artillery Regiment]] (1933-1934) and [[18th Artillery Regiment]] (1934-1935).<ref>[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/cehart.htm Lt. General Charles Edward Hart Memorial Page, Arlington National Cemetery.]</ref>\n\nIn 1935 Hart would be transferred to the [[United States Military Academy]] and receive a promotion to [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]]. At the Academy Hart would command Battery \"A\" and serve as an artillery instructor.<ref>[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/cehart.htm Lt. General Charles Edward Hart Memorial Page, Arlington National Cemetery.]</ref> Following his service at the Academy he would be transferred to [[United States Field Artillery School]] located in [[Fort Sill]], [[Oklahoma]] as an instructor in 1940. He would remain at the school until 1942 after the outbreak of [[World War II]].<ref>[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/cehart.htm Lt. General Charles Edward Hart Memorial Page, Arlington National Cemetery.]</ref>\n\n==World War II==\nOn January 31, 1941, Hart received a temporary promotion to the rank of [[Major]]. Later that year, while serving as an instructor in the Department of Gunnery at the [[United States Army Field Artillery School]], Hart received a permanent promotion to Major on June 12, 1941.<ref>Charles E. Hart: Official U.S. Army Register, Jan. 1, 1943., Government Printing Office, Washington, D.C., Department of the Army.</ref> He was then sent to [[Fort Leavenworth]], [[Kansas]] to attend the Command and General Staff School. Upon completing the course, he was again assigned to the Artillery School, this time as an instructor in the Department of Tactics.<ref>[https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ Charles E. Hart 1924, West Point Memorial Article] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408213009/https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ |date=April 8, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nWith America's entry into World War II in 1941, the military suffered from a lack of qualified officers to take command positions. It was under these circumstances in 1941 that Hart received a promotion to the temporary rank of Lieutenant Colonel on December 24, 1941.<ref>Charles E. Hart: Official U.S. Army Register, Jan. 1, 1943., Government Printing Office, Washington, D.C., Department of the Army.</ref> He would then be transferred to the II Corps during the planning for the invasion of North Africa where he would initially serve as the Assistant Commander of the II Corps Artillery.<ref>[https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ Charles E. Hart 1924, West Point Memorial Article] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408213009/https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ |date=April 8, 2014 }}</ref> With the commencement of [[Operation Torch]]  and the invasion of [[Algiers]] the II Corps under [[Major General]] [[Lloyd Fredendall]] would be designated the Central Task Force for the invasion.<ref>Howe, George F, \u201cUnited States Army in World War II Mediterranean Theater of Operations-Northwest Africa: Seizing the Initiative In the West\u201d, Washington, D.C.: Office of the Chief of Military History, Department of the Army, 1957</ref> It was during the operations in North Africa that Hart was elevated to the position of commander of the II Corps Artillery.<ref>[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/cehart.htm Lt. General Charles Edward Hart Memorial Page, Arlington National Cemetery.]</ref>\n\nOn January 12, 1943, Hart was given a temporary commission of [[Colonel]] and continued in command of the II Corps Artillery.<ref>Charles E. Hart: Official U.S. Army Register, Jan. 1, 1943., Government Printing Office, Washington, D.C., Department of the Army.</ref><ref>[https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ Charles E. Hart 1924, West Point Memorial Article] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408213009/https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ |date=April 8, 2014 }}</ref>  As the II Corps\u2019 Artillery Officer he was involved with the operations of the II Corps during the drive towards Tunis, including the U.S. defeats at the [[Battle of Sidi Bou Zid]] on February 14\u201317, 1943 and [[Kasserine Pass]] on February 19\u201322, 1943. Following the Allied defeats in February, Major General [[Lloyd Fredendall]] was transferred from command of the II Corps and replaced by Major General [[George S. Patton]] on March 6, 1943.<ref>Howe, George F, \u201cUnited States Army in World War II Mediterranean Theater of Operations-Northwest Africa: Seizing the Initiative In the West\u201d, Washington, D.C.: Office of the Chief of Military History, Department of the Army, 1957</ref>\n\nWith Patton in command, Hart moved to improve artillery operations. Concerned with his artillery air observation posts, he requested and received permission to add an air artillery officer to his staff. On March 8, 1943, Lieutenant [[Delbert L. Bristol]] was assigned on temporary duty. Under Hart's direction and with the blessing of Patton, Bristol developed the first Corps Air Artillery section in the entire U.S. Army.<ref>Raines, Edgar F., Jr., \u201cEyes of the Artillery: The Origins of Modern U.S. Army Aviation in WWII\u201d, Washington, D.C.: U.S. Army Center of Military History, 2000.</ref>\n[[File:Don Edwards with Lt General Hart in 1960.jpg|thumbnail|Lt. General Hart (left) presenting award to Specialist Donald B. Edwards at Army Air Defense Command HQ, Ent Air Force Base, Colorado Springs, Colorado, 1960]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hart, Charles E.}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Charles Hart (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Charles Edward Hart\n| image         = Lieutenant_General_Charles_Edward_Hart.png\n| caption       = Circa 1956-1960\n| birth_date    = June 17, 1900\n| death_date    = December 9, 1991 (aged 91)\n| birth_place   = [[Fort Washington, Maryland]]\n| death_place   = [[Fort Belvoir]], [[Virginia]]\n| placeofburial = [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance    = {{US}}\n| branch        = {{Army|United States}}\n| serviceyears  = 1924\u20131960\n| rank          = [[File:US-O9 insignia.svg|20px]] [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]]\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = \n| commands      = [[Artillery, 1st Infantry Division]]<br> [[Artillery, 7th Army]]<br>\n[[US Military Assistance Group, Greece]]<br> [[U.S. V Corps|V Corps]]<br>[[Commandant of the Artillery Center & School]]<br>[[Second United States Army|2nd Army]]<br>[[Army Air Defense Command]]\n| battles       = [[World War II]]\n| battles_label = \n| awards        = [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]]<br>[[Legion of Merit]] x2\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n}}\n\n'''Charles Edward Hart''' (June 17, 1900 \u2013 December 9, 1991) born in [[Fort Washington, Maryland]] was a [[General|Commanding General]] of the [[U.S. V Corps|V Corps]] (1954\u20131956) and Commanding General of the Army Air Defense Command (1957\u20131960). He died at [[Fort Belvoir]], [[Virginia]] at the age of 91.\n\n==Early life==\n'''Charles Edward Hart''' was born in Fort Washington, Maryland, the son of Dr. (Colonel) James William Hart and Grace Duncan Hart.<ref>[https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ West Point Memorial] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408213009/https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ |date=April 8, 2014 }}</ref> Hart was a descendant of Private Joseph Hart, a member of the 4th Virginia Regiment during the Revolutionary War.<ref>District of Columbia Sons of the American Revolution Application, National Number 23755.</ref> By 1910 the family had moved to Washington, D.C. where Hart's father had a general practice and served on the staff of the Veteran's Hospital.<ref>13th Federal Census, 1910, District of Columbia.</ref><ref>[https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ West Point Memorial] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408213009/https://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/7517/ |date=April 8, 2014 }}</ref> Eventually residing in Fort Hunt, Virginia, Hart would attend military drills with his father. After graduating from Western High School in Washington, D.C., Hart